recordings.type: alarm call, mew call, long call
recordings.rmk: from:"Some Skomer sounds", 2004, Rombout de Wijs. In 1982 and 1983 I was a research assistant on Skomer Island for counting, observing and ringing seabirds. In my spare time I made many pictures and also recorded sounds of several birds. The main purpose was to document the state of island life at that time, also enabling me to relive my stay (to some extent) in later years. Sound recordings were made with rather primitive means, two simple microphones mounted in the "focal point" of a plastic umbrella (used as a reflector), a Sony TCS-310 stereo cassette recorder and simple headphones. Only recently I decided to make them better available and therefore digitized them. From 3.5 hours of sounds I extracted this selection for audio cd.

After listening to the recording again, it is clear these are European herring gulls.  The location was an inland reservoir.  Herring, lesser black-backed, great black-backed and black-headed gulls all occur but this was before dawn and still dark. Many thanks.

The biotope consists of a bungalow park & holiday park in which many trees, low open deciduous wood, gardens and a lot of fresh open water, surrounded by: glasshouse horticulture companies with greenhouses, dune landscape and sea coast.
